<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="49" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName authority="Reuter, 1891" authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Nannocoris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nannocoris tuberculiferus" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculiferus">Nannocoris tuberculiferus Reuter, 1891</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="49" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="49">
Nomenclature. 
<bibRefCitation author="Reuter, OM" journalOrPublisher="Acta Societatis Scientiarum Fennicae" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" pagination="1 - 28" title="Monographia Ceratocombidarum orbis terrestris." volume="19" year="1891">Reuter (1891)</bibRefCitation>
described the subgenus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Schizoptera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schizoptera (Nannocoris)" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Nannocoris">Schizoptera (Nannocoris)</taxonomicName>
to accommodate two new species with distinctly elongated heads, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Schizoptera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schizoptera (Nannocoris) nebulifera" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nebulifera" subGenus="Nannocoris">Schizoptera (Nannocoris) nebulifera</taxonomicName>
Reuter, 1891 and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Schizoptera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schizoptera (Nannocoris) tuberculifera" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculifera" subGenus="Nannocoris">Schizoptera (Nannocoris) tuberculifera</taxonomicName>
Reuter, 1891. Whereas 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Schizoptera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schizoptera" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Schizoptera</taxonomicName>
is feminine, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Nannocoris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nannocoris" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Nannocoris</taxonomicName>
is masculine, because 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“coris”">&quot;coris&quot;</normalizedToken>
is Greek for 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“bug”">&quot;bug&quot;</normalizedToken>
and a noun with masculine gender. When 
<bibRefCitation author="McAtee, WL" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the United States National Museum" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" pagination="1 - 42" title="Revision of bugs of the family Cryptostemmatidae in the collection of the United States National Museum." url="https://doi.org/10.5479/si.00963801.67-2585.1" volume="67" year="1925">McAtee and Malloch (1925)</bibRefCitation>
elevated 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Nannocoris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nannocoris" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Nannocoris</taxonomicName>
to genus level, they failed to adjust the gender of previously described species from feminine to masculine and also treated their newly described species as feminine. Nevertheless, subsequent authors continued to treat 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Nannocoris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nannocoris" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Nannocoris</taxonomicName>
as feminine. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Nannocoris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nannocoris arenaria" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arenaria">Nannocoris arenaria</taxonomicName>
Blatchley, 1926 was corrected to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Nannocoris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nannocoris arenarius" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arenarius">Nannocoris arenarius</taxonomicName>
Blatchley, 1926 by 
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Henry (1988)</bibRefCitation>
without comment. We here adjust the genders to masculine for all remaining names that were originally treated as feminine and are not patronyms: 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. nebuliferus" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="nebuliferus">N. nebuliferus</taxonomicName>
Reuter, 1891; 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. tuberculiferus" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="tuberculiferus">N. tuberculiferus</taxonomicName>
Reuter, 1891; 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. capitatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="capitatus">N. capitatus</taxonomicName>
(Uhler, 1894); 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. nasus" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="nasus">N. nasus</taxonomicName>
McAtee &amp; Malloch, 1925; 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. flavomarginatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="flavomarginatus">N. flavomarginatus</taxonomicName>
McAtee &amp; Malloch, 1925.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="49" type="phylogeny and classification">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Phylogeny and classification.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="49">
A recent molecular phylogenetic analysis of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Nannocoris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nannocoris" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Nannocoris</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Frankenberg, S" journalOrPublisher="Organisms, Diversity, and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" pagination="211 - 224" title="Heads up: evolution of exaggerated head length in the minute litter bug genus Nannocoris Reuter (Hemiptera: Schizopteridae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13127-018-0361-y" volume="18" year="2018">Frankenberg et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
) included one North American specimen (UCR_ENT 00094252), a female from Texas that we have assigned to the new species 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. brevipilus" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="brevipilus">N. brevipilus</taxonomicName>
below. This taxon was recovered as part of the pricei species group that is diagnosed by the opening of the male-specific vertex gland being located in a posterior position, i.e. posteriorly on the vertex or on the pronotal collar. The opening is more anterior on the head in males of all other 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Schizopteridae" genus="Nannocoris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nannocoris" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Nannocoris</taxonomicName>
species we have examined (data not shown; see Figure 1 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Frankenberg, S" journalOrPublisher="Organisms, Diversity, and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" pagination="211 - 224" title="Heads up: evolution of exaggerated head length in the minute litter bug genus Nannocoris Reuter (Hemiptera: Schizopteridae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13127-018-0361-y" volume="18" year="2018">Frankenberg et al. [2018]</bibRefCitation>
for selected species) and it is absent in some species. Males of 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. arenarius" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="arenarius">N. arenarius</taxonomicName>
and the second newly described species, 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. anophorus" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="anophorus">N. anophorus</taxonomicName>
, share the pronotal position of the opening of the vertex gland. We therefore tentatively assign all three Nearctic species to the pricei species group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
